(99, 72, 4, 'https://youtu.be/gsXcGMNupOY?t=246', 1, '2023-01-20'),
(100, 7, 4, 'https://www.gd4h.org/index.php/2022/12/30/fencer-vs-fighter-a-case-study-on-how-adding-more-options-can-make-you-worse/', 1, '2023-01-20'),
(101, 6, 3, '<p><span style=\"color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Arial; font-size: 14.6667px; white-space: pre-wrap;\">It also helps to remind the defender that \"you can\'t win if they don\'t swing\". Running away won\'t help the defender, they have to try to bait the attacker into an attack that they think they can avoid.&nbsp;</span></p>', 1, '2023-01-20'),
(102, 11, 1, '<p>A modification to make this more representative is for the <b>[Tapper]</b> to bring the sword back and tap their shoulder with the blade instead of down to tap the ground. (Though this feels more awkward to do the taps with.)</p>', 1, '2023-01-20'),
(103, 51, 4, 'https://www.gd4h.org/index.php/2022/12/18/fck-the-finnish-chicken-a-case-study-of-cla-games-implementation/', 1, '2023-01-20'),
(104, 51, 4, 'https://www.gd4h.org/index.php/2022/12/18/revenge-of-the-finnish-chicken/', 1, '2023-01-20'),
(105, 31, 3, '<p>This game is hard to self-call so it works best with a judge.<br></p>', 13, '2023-01-20'),
(106, 82, 2, '<p>The purpose of this game is two fold.<br><br>1.&nbsp;&nbsp;Effective tactics to land a hit with your first strike.</p><p>2. Teach a lesson about how our perceptions limit us and that a parry can be as offensive as it is defensive.&nbsp;</p><p>At first defenders will be pretty cowed and very passive, as the game goes on you should see the defender get surer and surer in their parries and start punishing the attacker for sticking around after their strike. Eventually the Defenders will realise that it is a much smarter idea to rush the attacker and parry as they close the distance. DO NOT TELL THEM OR LEAD THEM TOWARDS THIS. It is important that the defenders figure this out themselves. While the game is always useful the most valuable thing it can do is teach fencer the importance of seizing control of the fight and fighting on their terms no matter if they think they are disadvantage or not.</p>', 8, '2023-01-24'),
(107, 82, 3, '<p>Depending on how adaptive the fencers are, getting the stage of the defender seizing the initiative can take 30-90 minutes of play. Make sure you are bringing them in regularly to discuss findings.</p>', 8, '2023-01-24'),
(108, 47, 3, '<p>Game names are cooler if they\'re alliterative. Otherwise why even bother.</p>', 6, '2023-01-26'),
(109, 34, 1, '<p>Even more variations:<br><u>Time Based</u>: Add a start line which is well out of engagement distance from the hole. Peasant starts at the start line and the timer says \'go\'. Every time the peasant fails (aka gets hit) they must go back to the start line and try again. Record how long in total time until they get the hit. Then switch and see if the new peasant can beat this time.<br><br><u>Head-To-Head Shootout</u>: Switch the roles every hit. Continue going until a peasant wins, and then their opponent fails to win when they are the peasant next. Addition of a 15 second \'shot clock\' makes it more expense and prevents a peasant who is on a need-to-win round from stalling too long before engaging. If no hit is recorded by 15 seconds it is a double out, aka a win for the king.</p>', 1, '2023-02-03'),
(110, 83, 3, '<p>It\'s not about going fast. It\'s about changing direction, changing speed, and provoking mistakes from the opponent.</p>', 14, '2023-02-14'),
(111, 84, 3, '		 			<p>This game is based on a game I played a long time ago, I think first at Longpoint 2016. In that version only the head was a target, and you had to hit the four quadrants of the head in order. This is that but with the full body instead of the head. I feel that it makes you think about fencing in interesting ways, because you need to target areas that you might not normally, and you need to pay attention to what your opponent is targeting.</p>		 		', 5, '2023-02-19'),
(112, 85, 2, 'Our main use case for this is practicing the zornhaw. For the thrusting side, parrying and then riposting with a stab is the best defensive option. If used for this reason, right of way is recommended, because priority to parry riposte encourages the zornhaw.&nbsp;', 5, '2023-02-19'),
(113, 85, 3, '<p>We kept score on this game twice, the first time both sides were required to start in shoulder guard, the result was out of 200 reps, cut won 123 times (61.5%), and thrust won 77 times (38.5%). The second time there was no restriction on starting position, and out of 200 reps cut won 112 times (56%), and thrust won 88 times (44%). Possible confounding factor is go-now boffers, some reps were done with them, and they probably favor the cut.&nbsp;</p>', 5, '2023-02-19'),
(114, 85, 4, 'https://www.gd4h.org/index.php/2023/02/17/cla-adventures-with-the-zornhaw/', 5, '2023-02-19'),
(115, 86, 2, '<p>This flips the script of the normal soviet foil game, usually the longsword side is the attacker and is mostly moving forward, but in this version it\'s a game of the longsword side trying to avoid getting doubled.&nbsp;</p><p>The variation adds another tactical layer of the game, as either side (but especially the longsword side) can now beat or parry in order to help them win. The longsword side must be careful though, because if they attempt a beat and miss, they lose that rep.&nbsp;</p>', 5, '2023-02-20'),
(116, 86, 3, '<p>In both variations, it\'s important that the dussack side be willing to eat a hit in order to double. If they are not willing to do this, then the game is either too strong for the longsword, or it becomes baseline soviet foil. The point of the game is to get the longsword side to pick their moments carefully in order to not double, so if the dussack side is not willing to double, the longsword side can\'t learn this. </p><p>On the flip side, it is not a valid tactic for the longsword side to use the threat of pain to discourage the dussack side from doubling. This is an element of buy-in that is required for the game to work correctly.&nbsp;</p>', 5, '2023-02-20'),
(117, 66, 3, '<p>This game is very violent, proceed with caution. Also works much better with steel than boffers.&nbsp;</p>', 5, '2023-02-20'),
(118, 51, 3, '<p>This game is called \"Finnish Chicken\" because it was introduced to us in the US by Finnish longsword coach Kristian Ruokonen. The way I initially understood it was that you were not allowed to retreat, I don\'t know if that was an original rule or not, but because of that the game became a game of chicken, seeing how close you can get before pulling the trigger on an attack or defense. Allowing retreats takes reduces the \"chicken\" aspect, and you can even play it like soviet foil if you want.&nbsp;</p>', 5, '2023-02-22'),
(119, 8, 4, 'https://www.gd4h.org/index.php/2023/01/20/the-direct-attack-drill-is-special-self-scaling-games/', 5, '2023-02-22'),
(120, 8, 3, '<p>This game is critical in teaching the \"ballistic passing step\" class of footwork/blade action. Getting it to manifest may take some specific coaching because there are alternate movement solutions that work equally well within the parameters of the game (IE a lunge). As soon as the fencer is able to produce the action, return to this game so they can practice it in an environment that affords efficient movement and is constantly varying (parameters change each rep with different distance).&nbsp;</p>', 5, '2023-02-22'),
(121, 87, 2, '<p>This is a variation of the soviet foil drill, the same skills must be used, but this time the fencers must complete the action by landing a hit after avoiding.&nbsp;</p>', 5, '2023-02-23'),
(122, 87, 3, '<p>Be careful with how you assign priority here, if you always give the attack to the person who moves forward without stopping, then the game will be broken because you can\'t lose by immediately running forward on \"fence.\" Even if someone was previously moving backwards, they can claim priority by stepping in with an attack first.</p>', 5, '2023-02-23'),
(123, 87, 1, '<p>I run this game with fencers starting in alber and having to chamber through high tag to attack. Lifting to high tag is your \'claim priority\' action, and if you lift and don\'t step forward + attack you lose priority again.</p>', 14, '2023-02-24');
INSERT INTO `infoList` (`infoID`, `gameID`, `infoMetaID`, `infoText`, `userID`, `infoDate`) VALUES
(124, 88, 2, '		 					 			<p>This is originally a more choreographed routine that I successively added more and more incompliance to until it became a game. If you just throw the rules down without doing the choreographed version I have no clue what would develop.</p><p>The pattern was intended to work on grip switches, Meyer\'s Circle, and lateral movement around to the right (Meyer\'s triangle step). Both fighters would essentially move in a mirrored pair each extending to longpoint, and then running-off with their cuts as they did a triangle step to the right and delivered the next cut with the other edge. In this case the cuts were canceling each other out, and it was kind of a conditioning drill.</p><p>By adding the competitive element of \"you can win by hitting the head\" it gave people the impetus to actually really try to break through the oberhau with the shillhau, driving towards the head. As people go they tend to get over-exuberant to break through and throw across the line rather than at the head. This is when the hands become a sensible target, as there is no longer the threat of getting hit in the head with a double. Thus \"swing for the head and try to create a wedge that goes through\" becomes the emergent mechanic rather than \"try to smash open their line\".</p><p>Also the cuts get really frantic so they get used to quick grip transitions under pressure. A few rounds of this does more than a whole session of breaking down the exact movement of the hand. The rule for chambering has proved largely unnecessary, as getting enough into your blow to stop theirs is of prime importance. Typically going so fast your get them in-between strikes hasn\'t been a good strat, but if you\'re faster you try to up the rate high enough that they are now throwing poor strikes that don\'t threaten.</p><p><b>In general hard hitting hasn\'t been my experience with emergent behavior but I would watch for it carefully.</b></p>		 				 		', 1, '2023-02-26'),
(125, 88, 3, '<p>Tends to work better from a counter-play game point of view if the start with opposite cuts. Ober vs shilhau.</p>', 1, '2023-02-26'),
(126, 89, 2, '		 			<p>After they got a chance to free sparing at an event, I saw one instructor tell another \"you fight like you\'re used to being the best fighter in your club. You\'re used to driving the fight and having them respond to you, but not so good at paying attention and responding to what the other fighter does.\" Which I thought was pretty good advice that I wouldn\'t have thought of.</p><p>This game was designed to be asymmetrical in nature, with the Despot being the role you put the \'better\' fencer into. They are now required to <u>force</u> a counter within the Rebel\'s chain of attacks; instead of just being able to take the <i>vor</i>&nbsp;off the bat, or bait them to overextend and use <i>nachrisen</i>. This is why I have the Despot shifting out after two failures in a row, because the better fighter will end up spending more time in this role.&nbsp;</p>		 		', 1, '2023-03-12'),
(127, 90, 3, '<p>You don\'t need full gear for this, but a mask is recommended so that swords don\'t come down and bonk them in the head. A mask is required if they are starting with the tips inline (and not over/past their heads.)</p><p>You probably want at least light gloves to prevent any swords being drawn through hands, and <b>check the swords for burs first!</b></p>', 1, '2023-03-15'),
(128, 90, 2, '<p>This is a fairly simple game, but a skill a lot of people have difficulty with. Encourage them to try many different strategies/direction for grabbing and pulling back, people often stick with the same (not working) approach and just think \"if only I did it a little faster next time!\"</p>', 1, '2023-03-15'),
(129, 91, 3, '		 			<p>This base version of this is essentially <a href=\"https://www.gd4h.org/hga/gameInfo.php?g=87\" target=\"_blank\">Pursuit Shuffle</a> played with socks.<br></p>		 		', 13, '2023-03-19'),
(130, 91, 2, '<p>I got the idea of fighting with socks from one of the other GD4H people, I don\'t remember who. These are the rules I use for it in my classes.<br></p>', 13, '2023-03-19'),
(131, 91, 1, '<p>Variation: front vs back</p><p>[A] can only score by hitting the back of their opponent\'s torso<br>[B] can only score by hitting the front of their opponent\'s torso<br><br>This version encourages offline movement and close-range fighting. And spin moves. It\'s good for getting people to try out different things with their footwork, though many of the movements that emerge won\'t be directly useful in fencing.<br><br></p>', 13, '2023-03-19'),
(132, 91, 1, '<p>Variation: hopping</p><p>Same rules as the basic version, except you can only move by hopping. Both feet must leave the ground and land at roughly the same time.</p><p>This is pretty physically demanding, and develops the ability to move explosively and absorb force when landing. Not recommended for beginners.<br></p>', 13, '2023-03-19'),
(133, 92, 2, 'This is designed to get people doing the basic motions of krumphau, zwerhau, and other crooked/shortened attacks. The attacker can\'t use straight cuts or thrusts because they will touch the buckler, so they have to find ways of going around the center.<br>', 13, '2023-03-19'),
(134, 92, 3, '<p>This game is not remotely balanced. If [A] is at all competent at krumphau or zwerhau they will probably win most of the time. But I find many beginners struggle with the krumphau in particular, and end up doing a weird oberhau or a bad parry instead of a motion which is actually crooked. This game will fix that problem very quickly.<br></p>', 13, '2023-03-19'),
(135, 92, 3, '<p>A non-game version of this, where [B] just stands still and [A] has to figure out how to hit them around the buckler, can also be useful for newbies.&nbsp; <br></p>', 13, '2023-03-19'),
(137, 78, 4, 'https://www.gd4h.org/index.php/2023/03/20/where-is-defend-the-wall/', 1, '2023-03-22'),
(138, 27, 4, 'https://www.gd4h.org/index.php/2023/03/20/where-is-defend-the-wall/', 1, '2023-03-22'),
(139, 12, 4, 'https://www.gd4h.org/index.php/2023/03/20/where-is-defend-the-wall/', 1, '2023-03-22'),
(140, 13, 4, 'https://www.gd4h.org/index.php/2023/03/20/where-is-defend-the-wall/', 1, '2023-03-22'),
(141, 64, 4, 'https://www.gd4h.org/index.php/2023/03/20/where-is-defend-the-wall/', 1, '2023-03-22'),
(142, 95, 2, '<p>This game is designed to encourage the zwerhaw. Like most zwerhaw games, it has paths to success that do not use the zwerhaw at all, so if you find your fencers are not using it, supplement with other games.&nbsp;</p><p>It can sometimes be hard to spot which edge someone is using, and which edge is which can get murky because the short edge person may tend to slowly turn the sword in their hand to make cutting with the short edge easier. Use your discretion in dealing with this and keep in mind whatever purpose you have in mind for the game.&nbsp;</p>', 5, '2023-03-22'),
(143, 96, 2, '<p>This is basically an attempt to capture modern sabre\'s \"Rock paper scissors\" vibe off the start lines, but without needing full sabre equipment or as much technical skill. The aim is to encourage split-second decision making, and being able to hedge instead of just picking blindly.&nbsp;</p>', 14, '2023-03-22'),
(144, 97, 2, '<p>This wasn\'t designed after the Star Wars fight, but once pointed out the name was too good to pass up.</p><p>The key for the <b>Jedi</b> is to be able to see the right moment to attack, as if they get parried they are at a huge disadvantage. The<b> General</b> instead learns to control their cutting guard/position of their crossguard to best cover themselves as they are doing their cutting actions. Because the <b>General</b> knows what openings they are giving the <b>Jedi</b> they can also be prepared to react to someone sniping in to the obvious opening, and create traps they can draw their opponent out with.</p>', 1, '2023-04-01'),
(145, 89, 1, '<p>Alternate way to rotate fencers:<br>2+ Rebels, 1 Despot , while one Rebel is fighting the others are waiting for their turn. If the Rebel loses (Despot win) the next Rebel gets their shot. If the Despot loses twice in a row to the same Rebel they get ousted and become a Rebel-in-waiting. This makes a rotation where the better fencers spend far more time as the Despot and the weaker ones are rotating through as Rebels.&nbsp;</p><p>It also makes for fun narratives/banter back and forth as people are winning and \'seizing power\'. If you have enough people maybe you could have multiple \'countries\' going, with the ever changing pool of Rebels constantly vying control of each?&nbsp;\\_()_/</p>', 1, '2023-04-08'),
(146, 98, 2, '<p>This is an inversion of the typical Right of Way order, in that it makes attacking very&nbsp; perilous. The idea is that each fighter should be trying to pressure their opponent to the edge of the ring before acting, where they will then be able to attack without a large disadvantage. Fighters who attack without consideration to where they are in the space will be at a significant disadvantage.</p>', 1, '2023-05-02'),
(147, 99, 2, '		 			<p>The purpose of this game is to have the <b>nach</b> fighter learn how to deal with a highly aggressive opponent without playing their game. So once the <b>vor</b> has attacked they need to either back out and let one of the incoming attacks whiff, or get in on a parry and lock up the attacks in the grapple.</p>		 		', 1, '2023-05-04'),
(148, 100, 2, '<p>The defender is learning to draw the attacker into overcommitting and collapsing the distance. The attacker learns to build an attack and create pressure without getting too close or too fast.</p>', 14, '2023-05-06'),
(149, 100, 3, '<p>I\'m like 50% sure this is already somewhere in the archive, just adding it in case it isn\'t.</p>', 14, '2023-05-06'),
(150, 101, 2, '		 			<p><b>Be very careful when playing this with steel</b>, as if people are new/frustrated they may escalate by just starting to smash through to the head harder. In that case it is best to play with foams, as having people escalate and try to crash to the head harder <i><u>is</u></i> part of the game.</p><p>Once people get the hang of it the game becomes more about tactics and timing that smashing through with the hardest attack. Being the first to attack has a huge advantage in terms of being able to break through the attack. But it also affords tactical superiority, because if they respond to the disadvantage with parrying instead of attacking you can then start feinting fast attacks to win. Likewise using distance to have them commit to attacking from to far away, and missing, or luring them too close to react to the direct attack, are also good strategies. In my experience they quickly figured out that repeatedly smashing swords wasn\'t all that helpful.</p>		 		', 1, '2023-06-01'),
(151, 80, 1, '		 			<p>Tried this again with priority added. There aren\'t typically a ton of doubles to begin with, however giving the priority rules really made people want to try <i>duplieren </i>a lot, so they have value just from that<i>.</i></p><p>Priority was assigned based on a counter-clockwise rotation starting at the foot. Which means if your attacking their left side the higher target has the priority. However if you manage to get to the other side of their body, like in a <i>duplieren</i>, it\'s higher priority the further around you go. So a <i>mutieren</i> would be a super high priority action. (<b>sacrifice throw always loses priority</b>)<br><img src=\"data:image/png;base64,\" data-filename=\"image.png\" style=\"width: 221.025px; height: 271.203px;\"><br></p>		 		', 1, '2023-06-05'),
(152, 102, 2, '<p class=\"MsoNormal\">As is probably obvious, this is based on a Rock-Paper-Scissors\r\npremise.<o:p></o:p></p><ul><li>1.2) If they attack directly to the head, parry<o:p></o:p></li><li>2.1) If they are parrying, attack the leg</li><li>2.2) If they attack the leg, counterattack to the head</li><li>3.1) If they counterattack to the head, engage with a parry</li><li>3.2) If they engage with a parry, don\'t respond and move\r\nbackwards</li><li>1.1) If they don\'t engage, attack directly.</li></ul><p class=\"MsoNormal\"><o:p></o:p></p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">The idea is that it forces fencers to start thinking about\r\nalternating tactics, and using meta-gaming strategy. If someone is always using\r\nthe same options without variety they will get destroyed by someone who can\r\nroll between them all as necessary.</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">The other way to do this is the Head-Leg-Parry  Ratchet version.\r\nThe Direct Attack version focuses more on getting people used to the concept strategic\r\nswitches, whereas the Ratchet version is more representative of how to use switches\r\nin approach during sparring.</p>', 1, '2023-06-17'),
(153, 103, 2, '<p class=\"MsoNormal\">As is probably obvious, this is based on a Rock-Paper-Scissors\r\npremise.<o:p></o:p></p><ol><li>If they are attacking directly, then parry; even\r\npre-emptively to bait a swing into it.</li><li>If they are parrying you, attack their legs. (Or just bait\r\nthem to parry pre-emptively)</li><li>If they are attacking your legs, attack directly.</li></ol><p class=\"MsoNormal\">The idea is that it forces fencers to start thinking about\r\nalternating tactics, and using meta-gaming strategy. If someone is always using\r\nthe same options without variety, they will get destroyed by someone who can\r\nroll between them all as necessary.</p><p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n</p><p class=\"MsoNormal\">The other way to do this is the <a href=\"https://www.gd4h.org/hga/gameInfo.php?g=102\" target=\"_blank\">Head-Leg-Parry, DirectAttack</a> version. The Direct Attack version focuses more on getting people used to\r\nthe concept strategic switches, whereas the Ratchet version is more\r\nrepresentative of how to use switches in approach during sparring.<o:p></o:p></p>', 1, '2023-06-17');
